  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I re-apply for an H1B after cancelled without prejudice?",
  "response": "If your H-1B visa petition was canceled without prejudice, you may have the opportunity to reapply. Here's a general outline of the steps you should consider for reapplying for an H-1B visa:\n\n1. **Understand Cancellation Without Prejudice**: First, ensure you fully understand the implications of the cancellation. \"Without prejudice\" means that the previous petition does not affect your ability to submit a new application. However, it's essential to verify the reasons for the cancellation and assess whether they can be addressed in your new petition.\n\n2. **Review Eligibility**: Make sure that you still meet the eligibility criteria for an H-1B visa. This generally includes having a job offer from a U.S. employer, the job must require specialized knowledge, and you need to have a relevant degree or equivalent experience.\n\n3. **Find a New Employer**: If applicable, you may need to secure a new employer willing to sponsor you for the H-1B visa. Your employer will need to file a new petition.\n\n4. **Gather Required Documentation**: Compile all necessary documentation for the new petition, which typically includes:\n   - Job offer letter\n   - Labor Condition Application (LCA)\n   - Evidence of your qualifications (degrees, transcripts, etc.)\n   - Any additional supporting documents.\n\n5. **File a New Petition**: Your employer must file a new H-1B petition on your behalf. This could be a new application for the H-1B cap (if applicable) or a non-cap petition if you are changing employers (porting) or changing status.\n\n6. **Pay Fees**: Ensure that all required fees are paid. Your employer is responsible for these fees, which include filing fees, anti-fraud fees, and possibly premium processing fees.\n\n7. **Consult an Immigration Attorney**: It is highly advisable to consult with an immigration attorney who can guide you through the process, especially since your previous petition was canceled. They can help ensure that all necessary steps are followed and that there are no issues in your new application.\n\n8. **Await Approval**: After filing, wait for the U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS) to process the new petition. Processing times can vary based on several factors, including the service center and whether you opted for premium processing.\n\n9. **Consider Alternatives**: Depending on your situation, it may be worth considering other visa options or pathways to stay compliant with U.S. immigration laws while your H-1B petition is being processed.\n\nRemember that immigration laws and policies can change, so it's important to stay up-to-date and seek professional advice tailored to your specific situation.",
